Hey Uber,  According to your website, we can CHOOSE our method to settle our outstanding payment. I don't think we were ever given an option. A google online can easily call out disputes about riders having to pay cancellation fees to the next uber driver, who were mercilessly made to collect your debts for you.  FYI, I am not even made aware of of my outstanding balance until I was in the middle of my ride. I paid to the driver, not wanting to make things difficult for him. Upon clarification, Uber explained that they have given me a $6 credit by mistake, hence the outstanding charges. It was by no means my fault and now the charge is sneakily imposed on me. It took me for than a week to use up the credits, and another month before my next uber ride. You made no effort to take back the credits before I used it nor make any attempts to inform me until a notification which was sent in the middle of my ride. It was too late to make any dispute then.   I don't think I ever feel safe to engage your services again. Driver not showing up and we cancel? Driver cancelling on us? Calling a ride by mistake and then cancelling within 5 seconds? Oh be prepared to fork out $6 cancellation charge. At this rate, you are more expensive than any other private transport provider in Singapore.

Dear Uber.  I was totally in shock when I was wrongfully charged for $24.54 when my fare should be $19.93! I only knew about the excess charge of $4.61 after my trip. From the email correspondences from your goodself, you explained that it's because I've changed my route. I will like to reemphasised that I didn't change my route at all! And you mentioned that it's because your driver actually took a longer route and not taking the suggested routes by Uber. Again, it's no fault of mine. I do not work for Uber and I do not know what's the terms of contract between your goodself and the driver. In your words, if your driver didn't follow the suggested route, why did you impose the additional $4.61 on the rider instead? And how can Uber wrongfully charge me for the additional $4.61 without my consent? Is that the correct business practice that you all should adopt? Do you just charge the rider as you deem fit without obtaining the consent from the rider? In this case, it's absolutely unsafe for us to leave our card details with you as we won't know when we will be charged unnecessarily? Looking back at all the emails you send me, you don't seem to feel that by charging rider without their consent is wrong. All your emails only mentioned you will refund me the balance without acknowledging my query on why you charge me without my consent. You are not a metered taxi. If you set a fare, I agree and you stick to it. That's how it works! It's a contract between yourself and the rider. And if you charge me for the wrong route taken, then in your words, shouldn't I seek compensation from you because your driver took a longer route and that results to my time loss? In your email, you mentioned I have issues with your driver, No! I have no issues with your driver. My ride was otherwise smooth if I wasn't wrongfully charged. So again, do not distort the facts. Please look into how you all should handle customer's payment details safely. Thank you.

I am lodging a complaint on the unprofessional and threatening behaviour of one of your drivers.   The driver arrived at Ikea pickup point on the second lane, and barely stopped at the uphill slope. I had two heavy Ikea bags and gestured for him to move forward as cars were coming in and it would be difficult to load the bags into the boot. He did not move his car. I waited for a taxi to go past as it was coming up the slope and the taxi driver had impatiently honked at another driver ahead before I crossed over and loaded the boot.   I got into the car without saying a word. The driver asked if I was happy with the service. I replied, 'Not particularly' (along this line). He then asked me to get out of the car and stated he would not drive me to my destination. I assure you if this sounds absurd and unbelievable, it happened exactly as I have described. The driver's car ought to have a video recording; feel free to verify that what I am relating is the absolute truth.  This driver was most determined at provoking me. I told him I would not do as he pleases. He then said he would drive me to the police station. I told him to do what he needed to do. He then drove around the Ikea dropoff point a number of times before calling the police on his mobile phone.   On the phone with the police, he stated that he was on the second lane because Uber drivers are not supposed to pick up at taxi stands. He then added that I was well aware of this. We had zero exchange on this, so it is perplexing that the driver would know what was in my head. It became apparent the driver had to lie to justify his absurd behaviour.  The driver was most selfish to throw this fracas, especially since he had picked up another Uberpool rider and so he was being most unprofessional and inconveniencing two riders at once. Please check with the the other rider if I had said a word upon entering the car. At no point during this incident did I rant, rave or even raise my voice and hurl verbal abuse. The driver is not the owner of me that he should think he can dictate my feelings, thoughts or actions. It is not as if he had greeted me politely and I had not responded. It is not as if he had graciously helped with my bags and I had been ungrateful. Even so, the driver should not feel at liberty to treat riders with so much disdain and disrespect at his fancy, especially when he is representing the Uber brand.  I called ber and connected with Christine and John, a supervisor, who stated there was nothing he could do to assist, while waiting for the police to arrive. It is most absurd that the police had to be called in, when I had done absolutely nothing to provoke the driver. Basically, the driver imagines riders who enter a car quietly ought to be treated badly, humiliated, and terrorised.   Threatening a passenger and asking her to get out of the car as a means to humiliate her when she had said absolutely nothing cannot possibly be acceptable behaviour of Uber drivers or be representative of Uber's standard.  Inspector Lau informed me that it was really unsafe for me to continue with this journey. I agreed. I got another ride, not with Uber.  Uber needs to do the right thing here and take heed of my complaint. This was most unacceptable and absurd service in this day and age. I will state the likes of such drivers will only tarnish the Uber brand. Kindly ensure that this matter receives the attention it deserves. There were 3 rides that I took, upfront fare was a certain amount. The fare was BEFORE discount, and the discount was supposed to be applied after the ride. I know this because for so many of the rides I have taken, the discount only got applied AFTER the ride. However, on these 3 particular rides, at the end of the rides, the fare became at least $5 to $6 MORE than the original fare I was initially shown.   I then contacted Uber regarding the fare being bloated after the ride  and guess what?? They adjusted the fare down to the original upfront fare, but CLAIMED that the bloated fare WAS the original fare, and hence, I did not get the discounts from the original upfront fare because that was supposed to be the discounted fare. Does that even make sense?? How can a fare be bloated up instead of getting discounted, at the end of a ride??   Morever, I took screenshots from various other rides I took during the same period, as well as noted ALL my evening rides  ALL these rides only had discount applied AFTER the ride! So, is Uber trying to cheat our money by doing this? Out of 20 rides, all upfront fare is original price, then slip 3 rides in and bloat the fare "by mistake" after the ride, then CLAIM that that was in fact, the original fare and the original upfront fare was the discounted fare??? I wouldn't have booked if I knew!  One particuler Uber operator, Naresh, was clearly lying!

Dear Uber  You've been changing your promotion code discount application rules for Singapore these past months.  Before (Jan to March), it was last in first out (LIFO) and on Thursday evenings when we received and input the new promotion code sent to us via email, our currently active promotion code (sometimes not fully utilised, eg only used 2/4 eligibility) would cease to work and we'd need to wait till Thursday midnight or Friday 6am to again get to enjoy our new promo code discount. There was also no simultaneous application like now for RIDEMORN and DAYRIDE (only one promotion code can be used at a time). Previously it would be one or the other depending on which we input first. We'd need to exhaust 4 trips (eg. RIDEMORN) with one before the other (DAYRIDE) would kick in.  Then in April, suddenly you got very liberal and changed the rules for Singapore to highest discount applies. We were also allowed to stack different promo code discounts like LiveUp $10 with say a $5 off (nett $15 off on our 10th LiveUp trips. Trips with $0 fares plus promo discounted fares towards the 9 LiveUp trip count. Fares with both the discount value (eg $5 off) were applied first then percentage discount (eg 50%) was applied to the remainder and fare charged; listed as Discount ($5 off) and Promotion (50% off amount). Also we were literally covered for promo code discounts from 126am, 610am and 10am to 12pm. EVERYONE WAS SUPER HAPPY AND CONTENT. Uber usage was very high.  NOW I HEAR THAT THIS WEEK, without ANY WARNING or NOTICE whatsoever, Uber in Singapore had regressed back to LIFO You've caught many Uber riders off guard. How? You've "kindly" given selected riders with 4 x $3 off, 2050% off (customised) promotion codes. By accepting them, they're no longer eligible for RIDEMORN, DAYRIDE or NIGHTRIDES. They'll need to use their active promo code or exhaust their eligibility. BACK TO THE STONE AGES again What the heck are you trying to do? Screw with your loyal riders in such a cruel and unscrupulous manner Why mess with a good thing that was working fine to everyone's satisfaction  This week, I've received a large number of complaints from my almost 9,500 FB members (https://www.facebook.com/groups/1013566295436747/) with angry complaints about usage and application of promo code discounts; along with improper LiveUp trip counter (not moving and should be entitled to their $10 off but denied due to insufficient trip count or "can't be combined with other promos.")  Things are seriously getting screwed up on your end when you're giving your customers surprises and conflicting replies. Please get all your foreign call centres' CSOs on the same page and give us all correct and consistent replies and the same and proper treatment. Their training and replies reflects very badly on Uber as a very disorganised company where "the left hand doesn't talk to the right hand." Total confusion and disharmony  Oh yes, with 9,500 members, IT IS VERY EASY to compare all your CSOs inconsistent and wrong replies. Get your act together please and ensure all your call centres are reading from the same rule book, ACTUALLY READ our message PROPERLY and THOROUGHLY, before just sending a "canned reply" that isn't even relevant to the issue/query.  Last, please read through your own online published LiveUp T&C (https://help.uber.com/h/afddb3fd59074609b9e743b6aa1aaa54) and SHOW US in A FB POST where it's says $0 trips aren't a trip as in "take 9 trips) and when trips aren't counted due to use with promotion code discounts. I CHALLENGE YOU to reply my comment in full and don't even dare to ask me to email you as all my issues are a consolidation of all my all my FB group members' complaints. I'm very sure even non members have these same problems and issues.  Admin and Founder Uber/Grab Singapore Riders and Drivers Sharing. https://www.facebook.com/groups/1013566295436747/
Thank you for this initiative.First saw this feature in the US Uber last year, glad to see us having this in Singapore as well.

My answer is C!! :)   uberPOOL pairs riders based on their destinations and routes.  uberPOOL allows riders likes us to benefit from lower prices due to economy of scale from riders sharing the same route.  Changing destination will bring inconvenience to fellow passengers and is irresponsible, even to the driver as well!  Also, changing the route halfway opens a can of worms. There will be problems such as calculation for price and route adjustments especially if there are other users sharing the ride.   I would suggest riders who are unsure of their destination to think twice before using uberPOOL, and to instead consider under professional services from UBER such as UberX. This way we can create a better UBER community and have a better UBER experience :)

Uberpool will match us with another fellow passenger in the same area heading towards the same direction and saving us up to 40% off a uber x ride.   It will be inconsiderate of us if we change our destination abruptly during the trip resulting in delayed time of arrival of others. Thus this system of booking a ride is fair for everyone.   If we need foresee the need to change the destination during the trip, we should book a uber x instead.

Answer is C ..  uberPool matches riders with similar travelling routes. Riders who request for uberPool share their ride in exchange for a lower fares. If given a scenario Rider change destination then its inconvenience to fellow passengers and also will make rider time longer for others. So Riders are not allowed to change their destination after they have requested a ride.  If a rider wants to change the destination then no other option than to book new uberPool. If unsure where you are heading always book UberX which gives you flexibility of destination change.

I would like to highlight my disappointment with my recent Uber experience.  For background, when using Uber promotional codes, the upfront fare reflected on my Uber application has always been without the promotion value applied. On my latest trip applying the SAVEFIVE code, I only realised after seeing the receipt that the upfront fare had already incorporated the discount after applying promotional code (i.e. I paid $5 more than I expected).  I wrote in to Uber support to check on this issue, and had I been told that the upfront fare will always reflect the fare after incorporating the promotional value, that would be the end of the story. Instead, the response given was that sometimes the upfront fare incorporates the promotional value, sometimes it doesnt, but dont worry because the correct fare will be reflected in your receipt (see screenshot). This suspenseful game of Uber promotional code roulette speaks of a lack of transparency on fares and a principled approach on how promotional fares are reflected in the upfront fare. C: 2 minutes!   The 2minute waiting policy is a guideline that Uber sets for all riders. Because uberPOOL trips can involve multiple riders, inconsiderate behavior by anyone will affect the trip experience of other riders. The policy is a guideline to riders, so that they know they should not make you wait. Should they take longer than 2 minutes to enter your car, please use your best judgement as to whether or not to cancel the trip. It is always best to give the riders a call after about a minute of waiting. Riders will be charged a cancellation fee if their ride is cancelled due to prolonged wait.

post_comment: C  2 minutes is the maximum waiting time.   Any longer the driver are required to cancel as it is not right to let other uberpool riders wait for you. Cancellation charges of $6 will be levied on you.  Always be ready at pickup point when you book UberPool.
The correct answer will be 2 minutes of waiting. As a rider, i will always reach picking up point before i book for Uberpool. It is a form of considerate to other riders.

Of course there will be a limitation of time for the UberPool driver to wait you upon arriving or once they've arrived at your location since they need to make more other stuffs, specially for parttime workers. So, literally the limit time that they will give you is 2 minutes, so C will be the best answer

Answer: C. Driver's contact number  Uber implemented its numbermasking technology that will "disguise" personal numbers so Singapore Uber drivers who call from their mobile devices will not be able to see the customer's mobile number and vice versa.  Instead, they will automatically be routed through an encrypted number.  Drivers and riders will then communicate through "dummy" numbers, essentially a forwarding number, designed to block the true caller IDs of both the driver and passenger.

If they follow UG's booking fixed fare models, they could start off with GrabCar Economy and UberX like fixed fare trip bookings. If ambitious, they can even progress to a GrabShare and UberPool fixed trip option.  They could also offer promo codes to gain market share from Uber Ang Grab, kicking off another free for all promo code war. ComfortDelGro recently have already been announcing promo codes regularly and with their deep pockets. Combined with Premier and TransCab, this formidable taxi alliance or cartel combined could possibly outlast both Uber and Grab in a no holds bar price/promo code war. Uber and Grab have already slowed down their promo codes to a crawl and dripping trickle. Can Uber and Grab survive the onslaught of the combined taxi alliance/cartel? They may be even forced to form an unlikely and unholy alliance to fend off the competition from the new taxi juggernaut and be completely steamrolled!  Worst is taxis will have the best competitive advantage or ace in the whole of all. Taxis will be able to pickup adults with children under 1.35m as they have a LTA exemption. Good news for Uber and Grab drivers' headaches with those class of riders, plus these class of riders themselves not having to fear being rejected.  But the added competition for normal rides will become more fierce given the sheer size of the combined ComfortDelGro, Premier and TransCab (for now with HDT and SMRT waiting in the wings). Will Uber and Grab be able to handle the onslaught of the new monolith?  Drivers may defect on masse together with fare sensitive riders who have no brand loyalty. It could be an unexpected windfall for both as well as the taxi alliance with their many empty taxis gathering dust in their parking lot. The only barrier for drivers will be the taxi vocational driving license (TDVL). They were all set to take the PDVL (private) but may rethink TVDL now and need longer to obtain it than a PDVL. Existing taxi drivers who jumped ship to Uber or Grab will be able to transition back more easily. Those taxi drivers who were considering a move would probably stay out for now and have a wait and see perspective.  One thing is for sure. More likely than not it will be the rider who will once again be "king" and in the cat bird seat!   Time will tell who drivers will ultimately gravitate to. It's time for Uber and Grab to soon reassess many things like revising their partners' compensation, incentives, possibly personal welfare too like offering medical benefits for a start. They'll need to also reexamine their rider retention with lower fares and capped surges like in the Philippines, a new promo code strategy and ways to add value.   Grab has the obvious edge having diversified into so many other ventures. But how much it'll add to their bottom line, no one knows. Clearly it's up to Uber now to do more planning and strategising as they're clearly at the most disadvantage. Hopefully they will finally be forced to offer a customer service phone hotline, something they've long resisted and riders have been clamouring for.  It is going to be an extremely interesting couple of months to come. With the impending regulatory changes to PHV drivers and companies on top of the looming new form of fare competition, riders will be licking their lips with anticipation of being spoilt for choice and lower fares overall. My 2 cents.  Mervyn Tan Jui Meng Group Admin and Founder https://www.facebook.com/groups/1013566295436747/
